Below is a **single, self‑contained description** of the OCaml binding for the
BlockSci C++ iterator.  
It contains

* the public OCaml interface (`blocksci.mli`);
* the C‑/C++‑level stub file (`blocksci_stubs.c`) that talks to the BlockSci
  library and to the OCaml runtime;
* a short “how to compile” note.

You can copy‑paste the two source fragments into a directory, add the real
BlockSci header (`blockscicpp.h`) and the library (`-lblockscicpp`) and you will
have a functional OCaml module that lets the user write

```ocaml
Blocksci.iter_blocks (fun blk ->
  Printf.printf "height=%d hash=%s txs=%d\n%!"
    blk.Blocksci.height blk.Blocksci.hash blk.Blocksci.tx_count)
```

---

## 1. Public OCaml interface – `blocksci.mli`

```ocaml
(** {1 BlockSci OCaml bindings} *)

(** A minimal description of a Bitcoin block.  The fields are chosen to be
    representative; more fields can be added later without breaking the ABI. *)
type block = {
  height    : int;      (** Block height (0 = genesis) *)
  hash      : string;   (** Hex‑encoded block hash *)
  timestamp : float;    (** POSIX time in seconds *)
  tx_count  : int;      (** Number of transactions in the block *)
}

(** [iter_blocks f] walks the whole blockchain using BlockSci’s native C++
    iterator.  For each block the callback [f] is invoked with a record of type
    {!block}.  The callback runs inside the OCaml runtime; if it raises an
    exception the iteration stops and the exception propagates to the caller. *)
val iter_blocks : (block -> unit) -> unit
```

*Why this shape?*  
`block` is a plain OCaml record – cheap to allocate and easy for OCaml users to
pattern‑match on.  The only exported function is the iterator; opening/closing
the database is handled internally by the stub (BlockSci already provides a
process‑wide singleton).  If you need more control you can later add
`open_db : string -> unit` and `close_db : unit -> unit`.

---

## 2. C/C++ stub – `blocksci_stubs.c`

> **Important:** The file must be compiled with a C++ compiler (`g++`/`clang++`)
> because it includes BlockSci’s C++ headers and uses C++ objects.
> The file is written in “C‑style” (only `extern "C"` for the entry points) so
> that the OCaml build system can treat it as a normal C stub.

```c
/* blocksci_stubs.c  –  OCaml <-> BlockSci glue
 *
 * Compile with a C++ compiler, e.g.:
 *   ocamlc -c -ccopt -std=c++17 blocksci_stubs.c
 *   ocamlopt -c -ccopt -std=c++17 blocksci_stubs.c
 *
 * Link with the BlockSci C++ library:
 *   ocamlopt -o my_program unix.cmxa blocksci.cmx blocksci_stubs.o -lblockscicpp
 */

#include <caml/mlvalues.h>
#include <caml/memory.h>
#include <caml/alloc.h>
#include <caml/callback.h>
#include <caml/fail.h>
#include <caml/custom.h>
#include <caml/signals.h>
#include <caml/threads.h>   /* for caml_release_runtime_system / reacquire */
#include <exception>
#include <string>

/* ------------------------------------------------------------------ */
/*  Include the real BlockSci C++ header.  Replace the path if needed. */
#include "blockscicpp.h"          /* <-- your real BlockSci header */

/* ------------------------------------------------------------------ */
/*  Helper: convert a native BlockSci::Block (or whatever the iterator yields)
 *  into an OCaml value of type [block] (the record defined in the .mli).
 *
 *  The layout of the OCaml record is:
 *
 *    0 : height    (int)
 *    1 : hash      (string)
 *    2 : timestamp (float)
 *    3 : tx_count  (int)
 *
 *  The tag of the block record is 0 (the only constructor).
 */
static value caml_of_block(const BlockSci::Block &blk)
{
  CAMLparam0();
  CAMLlocal1(vblk);               /* the OCaml block we are building */

  /* Allocate a block with 4 fields and tag 0. */
  vblk = caml_alloc(4, 0);

  /* height – int32 in OCaml */
  Store_field(vblk, 0, Val_int(blk.height()));

  /* hash – copy the hex string (BlockSci returns std::string) */
  Store_field(vblk, 1, caml_copy_string(blk.hash().c_str()));

  /* timestamp – OCaml float */
  Store_field(vblk, 2, caml_copy_double(blk.timestamp()));

  /* tx_count – int */
  Store_field(vblk, 3, Val_int(blk.tx_count()));

  CAMLreturn(vblk);
}

/* ------------------------------------------------------------------ */
/*  The exposed OCaml primitive.
 *
 *  Signature in OCaml:   (block -> unit) -> unit
 *
 *  The callback is invoked for each block.  If the OCaml callback raises,
 *  we propagate the exception out of the C++ loop so that the user sees it.
 */
CAMLprim value blocksci_iter_blocks(value cb)
{
  CAMLparam1(cb);
  CAMLlocal1(vblk);               /* reused for each iteration */

  /* Basic sanity check – the argument must be a closure */
  if (!Is_block(cb))
    caml_invalid_argument("Blocksci.iter_blocks: argument is not a function");

  /* --------------------------------------------------------------
   *  Walk the blockchain.
   *
   *  We *do not* release the OCaml runtime here because the iteration is
   *  usually fast enough and keeping the runtime locked simplifies exception
   *  handling.  If you have a *very* large chain and want other OCaml threads
   *  to run concurrently you can surround the inner loop with
   *
   *      caml_release_runtime_system();
   *      … do work …
   *      caml_acquire_runtime_system();
   *
   *  but then you must also protect the callback value with a global root.
   *  The simple version below is sufficient for most use‑cases.
   * -------------------------------------------------------------- */
  try {
    BlockSci::BlockIterator it = BlockSci::begin();   /* start of chain */
    BlockSci::BlockIterator end = BlockSci::end();    /* past‑last */

    for (; it != end; ++it) {
      /* Convert the native block to an OCaml value */
      vblk = caml_of_block(*it);

      /* Call the OCaml closure.  caml_callback_exn lets us detect
       * exceptions without aborting the C++ stack. */
      value result = caml_callback_exn(cb, vblk);

      if (Is_exception_result(result)) {
        /* Propagate the OCaml exception to the caller. */
        caml_raise(result);
      }
    }
  }
  catch (const std::exception &e) {
    /* Convert any C++ exception into an OCaml Failure. */
    caml_raise_failure(caml_copy_string(e.what()));
  }
  catch (...) {
    caml_raise_failure(caml_copy_string("Blocksci: unknown C++ exception"));
  }

  CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* ------------------------------------------------------------------ */
/*  Register the primitive with OCaml.  The name must match the one used
 *  in the .mli (via an external declaration or by using the same name as
 *  the OCaml function).  Here we rely on the default naming convention:
 *
 *      external iter_blocks : (block -> unit) -> unit = "blocksci_iter_blocks"
 *
 *  No explicit registration table is required.
 */
```

### 2.1  What the stub does, step by step  

| Step | What happens | Why it matters |
|------|--------------|----------------|
| **`caml_of_block`** | Packs the C++ `BlockSci::Block` fields into an OCaml record (`block`). | Keeps the OCaml‐visible type pure and avoids exposing any C++ objects to the GC. |
| **Argument sanity** | Checks that the OCaml argument is a closure (`Is_block`). | Gives a clear error if the user passes something else. |
| **Iteration** | Uses BlockSci’s `begin()` / `end()` iterator pair. | Mirrors the native C++ API; no extra copying of the whole chain. |
| **Callback** | Calls `caml_callback_exn`. If the result is an exception (`Is_exception_result`) we re‑raise it. | Guarantees that OCaml exceptions abort the iteration cleanly and propagate to the caller. |
| **Exception handling** | Catches `std::exception` and unknown exceptions, turning them into `Failure`. | Prevents the C++ exception from unwinding through the OCaml runtime (which would abort the program). |
| **GC safety** | `CAMLparam`/`CAMLlocal` macros protect the OCaml values (`cb`, `vblk`) from the GC while the C++ code runs. | Guarantees that the GC does not move or collect the values while we are still using them. |

