## 3. How to compile & link

Assuming the files are named **`blocksci.mli`**, **`blocksci.ml`** (empty, just to
force the module) and **`blocksci_stubs.c`**, and that BlockSci’s header is
`blockscicpp.h` and the library is `-lblockscicpp`:

```sh
# 1. Compile the stub with a C++ compiler (use the same flags as OCaml)
ocamlc -c -ccopt -std=c++17 blocksci_stubs.c

# 2. Compile the OCaml interface (no implementation needed)
ocamlc -c blocksci.mli
ocamlopt -c blocksci.ml   # empty file, just to create blocksci.cmx

# 3. Build a program that uses the binding
ocamlopt -o myprog unix.cmxa blocksci.cmx blocksci_stubs.o -lblockscicpp
```

If you are building a library instead of an executable, replace `ocamlopt`
with `ocamlopt -shared` (or `ocamlc -a`) and link the resulting `.cmxa`/`.a`
into your final program.

---

## 4. Full example program (optional)

```ocaml
(* test.ml *)
let () =
  Blocksci.iter_blocks (fun blk ->
    Printf.printf "height=%d hash=%s txs=%d time=%.0f\n%!"
      blk.Blocksci.height blk.Blocksci.hash blk.Blocksci.tx_count blk.Blocksci.timestamp)
```

Compile:

```sh
ocamlopt -o test unix.cmxa blocksci.cmx blocksci_stubs.o -lblockscicpp test.ml
```

Running `./test` will print one line per block, proving that the OCaml callback
is executed for each native BlockSci iterator step.

